shim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Carter","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a transporter of goods, from Middle English <i>carter(e)</i> ‘carter’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>car(e)tier</i>, Old French <i>charetier</i>, medieval Latin <i>carettarius</i>, <i>carettator</i>). The Old French word coalesced with the earlier Middle English word <i>cart(e)</i> ‘cart’, which is from either Old Norse <i>kartr</i> or Old English <i>cræt</i>, both of which, like the Late Latin word, were probably derived from Celtic. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","Irish: shortened form of   McCarter  .","Americanized form of German   Karter   ‘carder’."],"variants":[{"name":"Charman","meanings":["English (Sussex and Surrey): occupational name for a carter, carrier, or coachman, from Middle English (Old French) <i>char</i>, <i>car</i> ‘car, cart, carriage’ + Middle English <i>man</i> ‘man’. Compare   Carter   and   Carman   2.","English (Sussex and Surrey): occupational name for someone who did odd jobs, from Middle English <i>char(re)</i>, <i>chere</i> (Old English <i>cier(r)</i>, <i>cer(r)</i>, <i>cear(r)</i>, <i>cær(r)</i>) ‘turn (of activity), small job, chore’ + <i>man</i>. Compare   Carman   2.","In some cases probably also an Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Čarman</b> (see   Carman   5)."]},{"name":"Chartier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Normand, Jacques, Marcel, Adelard, Alcide, Emile, Gilles, Raoul, Rosaire, Alphonse.","French: shortened form of <i>charretier</i>, an occupational name for a carter, from an agent derivative of Old French <i>charette</i> ‘cart’.","French Canadian: altered form of English   Carter  , a cognate of 1 above. Compare   Sharkey   and   Shorkey  ."]},{"name":"Karter","meanings":["German: occupational name for a carder (someone who prepares wool for spinning), from Middle High German <i>karter</i>. Compare   Carter  ."]},{"name":"McCarter","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   McArthur  ."]},{"name":"Carrier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Marcel, Emile, Lucien, Cecile, Alain, Gaetan, Gilles, Jacques, Laurent, Normand.","English and southern French: from Middle English, Old French <i>car(r)ier</i> (from Late Latin <i>carrarius</i>, a derivative of <i>carrum</i> ‘cart, wagon’, a word of Gaulish origin), an occupational name for a carter (see   Carter  ), in French also for a cartwright. Compare French   Charrier  .","French: occupational name for a stonemason or quarryman, <i>carrier</i>. Compare   Coyer  ."]},{"name":"Cartman","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): occupational name from Middle English <i>cartman</i> ‘man who operated a cart for the transport of goods’. Compare   Carter  .","Americanized form of German <b>Kartmann</b> (see   Kartman  )."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":55,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdi